************** G E N E R A L   I N F O R M A T I O N *************2125 1451   22
                                                                  2125 1451   23
This evaluated data file is based on a software system built      2125 1451   24
around the nuclear model code TALYS [kon23], version 2.0. It is   2125 1451   25
part of a large collection of isotopic evaluations, all created by2125 1451   26
running the system with either adjusted or default input          2125 1451   27
parameters. This means that the data in the entire collection have2125 1451   28
been tested in detail for many isotopes against individual        2125 1451   29
experimental data, while for other isotopes it is only as good as 2125 1451   30
the global quality of TALYS at the moment. The mutual quality of  2125 1451   31
all individual data files is however consistent: The same set of  2125 1451   32
nuclear models is used and, equally important, the same ENDF-6    2125 1451   33
formatting procedures for each isotope. The data file has been    2125 1451   34
created automatically using the ENDF-6 format generator TEFAL.    2125 1451   35
                                                                  2125 1451   36
The resulting data file provides a complete representation of     2125 1451   37
nuclear data needed for transport, activation, damage, heating,   2125 1451   38
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2125 1451   39
neutron energy range from 1.e-11 to 200. MeV.                     2125 1451   40
                                                                  2125 1451   41
All transport and activation data for neutrons, charged particles,2125 1451   42
photons and residual nuclides are filed. This includes cross      2125 1451   43
sections, angular distributions, double-differential spectra,     2125 1451   44
isomeric production, discrete and continuum photon production     2125 1451   45
cross sections, residual production cross sections and recoils.   2125 1451   46
This general purpose evaluation can thus be used as both          2125 1451   47
transport and activation library.                                 2125 1451   48
                                                                  2125 1451   49
A complete set of covariance data is included, which is stored    2125 1451   50
in MF31-40.                                                       2125 1451   51
                                                                  2125 1451   52
                      Resonance Range                             2125 1451   53
                                                                  2125 1451   54
  --------------------------------------------------------------- 2125 1451   55
  --------------------------------------------------------------- 2125 1451   56
                                                                  2125 1451   57
  General methodology: The global approach considered in this     2125 1451   58
          work is presented in the following papers:              2125 1451   59
          (1) Modern nuclear data evaluation with the TALYS       2125 1451   60
              code system, A.J. Koning and D. Rochman,            2125 1451   61
              A.J. Koning and D. Rochman,                         2125 1451   62
              Nuclear Data Sheets 113 (2012) 2841.                2125 1451   63
          (2) TENDL: Complete Nuclear Data Library for            2125 1451   64
              Innovative Nuclear Science and Technology,          2125 1451   65
              A.J. Koning, D. Rochman, J.Ch Sublet, N. Dzysiuk,   2125 1451   66
              M. Fleming and S. van der Marck,                    2125 1451   67
              Nuclear Data Sheets 155 (2019) 1.                   2125 1451   68
                                                                  2125 1451   69
  MF2:  Resolved resonance range  (RRR)                           2125 1451   70
       The RRR was generated with TARES-1.4                       2125 1451   71
       The unresolved resonance range is obtained from the TALYS  2125 1451   72
       code.                                                      2125 1451   73
                                                                  2125 1451   74
  MF33 in the resonance range:                                    2125 1451   75
  The MF33 in the resonance range is obtained by using a number   2125 1451   76
  of MF2 random files. There is therefore a consistency           2125 1451   77
  between the MF2 random and the MF33.                            2125 1451   78
  MF32:                                                           2125 1451   79
  The MF32 contains the resonance parameters, uncertainties and   2125 1451   80
  some correlation. These values are used to generate random      2125 1451   81
  MF2, taking advantage of the code ENDSAM from L. Plevnik and    2125 1451   82
  G. Zerovnik from JSI, Slovenia (thanks to A. Trkov, IAEA).      2125 1451   83
                                                                  2125 1451   84
***************************** T A L Y S **************************2125 1451   85
                                                                  2125 1451   86
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   2125 1451   87
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      2125 1451   88
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    2125 1451   89
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range. This is     2125 1451   90
achieved by implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into  2125 1451   91
a single code system. This nuclear data file is based on a        2125 1451   92
theoretical analysis that utilizes the optical model, compound    2125 1451   93
nucleus statistical theory, fission, direct reactions and         2125 1451   94
pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with databases and      2125 1451   95
models for nuclear structure. The following output of TALYS is    2125 1451   96
stored in this data file:                                         2125 1451   97
                                                                  2125 1451   98
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   2125 1451   99
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     2125 1451  100
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 2125 1451  101
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   2125 1451  102
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                2125 1451  103
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   2125 1451  104
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    2125 1451  105
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        2125 1451  106
- Recoil data                                                     2125 1451  107
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           2125 1451  108
- Total particle energy spectra                                   2125 1451  109
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      2125 1451  110
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        2125 1451  111
- Residual production cross sections                              2125 1451  112
                                                                  2125 1451  113
For a description of the used nuclear models and their            2125 1451  114
parameterization we refer to [kon19]. If for this specific        2125 1451  115
nuclide we deviate from the global parameterization, it is made   2125 1451  116
explicit above under Nuclide Specific Information.                2125 1451  117
                                                                  2125 1451  118
***************** F I L E   I N F O R M A T I O N ****************2125 1451  119
                                                                  2125 1451  120
##### MF1: GENERAL INFORMATION                                    2125 1451  121
                                                                  2125 1451  122
- MT451    : Descriptive data and directory                       2125 1451  123
                                                                  2125 1451  124
This text and the full directory of used MF/MT sections.          2125 1451  125
                                                                  2125 1451  126
##### MF2: RESONANCE PARAMETERS                                   2125 1451  127
                                                                  2125 1451  128
- MT151    : Resonance parameters                                 2125 1451  129
                                                                  2125 1451  130
Details about the origin of the resonance parameters for this     2125 1451  131
nuclide are given above in this description. In general, both a   2125 1451  132
Resolved and an Unresolved Resonance Range are given.             2125 1451  133
                                                                  2125 1451  134
##### MF3: REACTION CROSS SECTIONS                                2125 1451  135
                                                                  2125 1451  136
All the data present in the following MT-sections have been       2125 1451  137
calculated with TALYS, possibly normalized to experimental data.  2125 1451  138
If the maximal cross section in an excitation function over the   2125 1451  139
whole energy range does not exceed 1.e-9 b, the MT-number is not  2125 1451  140
included. Cross sections lower than 1.e-20 b are assumed to have  2125 1451  141
no physical meaning and are set to zero. All MT numbers extend up 2125 1451  142
to the highest incident energy.                                   2125 1451  143
The following reaction channels/MT numbers are generally included:2125 1451  144
                                                                  2125 1451  145
- MT1      : Total cross section                                  2125 1451  146
                                                                  2125 1451  147
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range,    2125 1451  148
or partly reproduced using experimental data.                     2125 1451  149
                                                                  2125 1451  150
- MT2      : Elastic scattering cross section                     2125 1451  151
                                                                  2125 1451  152
Obtained by subtracting the non-elastic cross section from the    2125 1451  153
total cross section.                                              2125 1451  154
                                                                  2125 1451  155
- MT3      : Non-elastic cross section                            2125 1451  156
                                                                  2125 1451  157
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range.    2125 1451  158
                                                                  2125 1451  159
- MT4      : Total inelastic cross section                        2125 1451  160
                                                                  2125 1451  161
Sum of MT=51-91.                                                  2125 1451  162
                                                                  2125 1451  163
- MT5      : (n,anything) cross section                           2125 1451  164
                                                                  2125 1451  165
MT5 contains the reactions which can not be stored in any other   2125 1451  166
MT-number. The information of MF3/MT5 can be combined with        2125 1451  167
MF6/MT5 to obtain residual production cross sections particle     2125 1451  168
production cross sections and (double-)differential cross         2125 1451  169
sections.                                                         2125 1451  170
                                                                  2125 1451  171
- MT16     : (n,2n) cross section                                 2125 1451  172
- MT17     : (n,3n) cross section                                 2125 1451  173
- MT22     : (n,na) cross section                                 2125 1451  174
- MT28     : (n,np) cross section                                 2125 1451  175
- MT51-90  : (n,n') cross section for 1st-40th excited state      2125 1451  176
- MT91     : (n,n') continuum cross section                       2125 1451  177
- MT102    : (n,gamma) cross section                              2125 1451  178
- MT103    : (n,p) cross section                                  2125 1451  179
- MT104    : (n,d) cross section                                  2125 1451  180
- MT105    : (n,t) cross section                                  2125 1451  181
- MT106    : (n,h) cross section                                  2125 1451  182
- MT107    : (n,a) cross section                                  2125 1451  183
- MT600-610: (n,p) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       2125 1451  184
- MT649    : (n,p) continuum cross section                        2125 1451  185
- MT650-655: (n,d) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        2125 1451  186
- MT699    : (n,d) continuum cross section                        2125 1451  187
- MT700-705: (n,t) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        2125 1451  188
- MT749    : (n,t) continuum cross section                        2125 1451  189
- MT750-755: (n,h) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        2125 1451  190
- MT799    : (n,h) continuum cross section                        2125 1451  191
- MT800-810: (n,a) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       2125 1451  192
- MT849    : (n,a) continuum cross section                        2125 1451  193
                                                                  2125 1451  194
##### MF4: ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES           2125 1451  195
                                                                  2125 1451  196
We use MF4 for the neutron scattering angular distribution for    2125 1451  197
discrete levels.                                                  2125 1451  198
                                                                  2125 1451  199
- MT2      : Elastic angular distribution                         2125 1451  200
                                                                  2125 1451  201
The flag LTT=3 is used to indicate a switch at some high energy,  2125 1451  202
generally 50 MeV, from a Legendre representation to a tabulated   2125 1451  203
representation. For incident energies below this energy, the      2125 1451  204
Legendre coefficients are given on a sufficiently precise energy  2125 1451  205
grid. They are a sum of calculated Legendre coefficients for      2125 1451  206
compound nucleus and shape-elastic scattering. For higher         2125 1451  207
incident energies, relative angular distributions are tabulated   2125 1451  208
on an angular grid.                                               2125 1451  209
                                                                  2125 1451  210
- MT51-70  : (n,n') angular distribution for 1st-20th state       2125 1451  211
- MT600-610: (n,p) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        2125 1451  212
- MT650-655: (n,d) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         2125 1451  213
- MT700-705: (n,t) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         2125 1451  214
- MT750-755: (n,h) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         2125 1451  215
- MT800-810: (n,a) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        2125 1451  216
                                                                  2125 1451  217
##### MF6: PRODUCT ENERGY-ANGLE DISTRIBUTIONS                     2125 1451  218
                                                                  2125 1451  219
In MF6 we store all secondary energy, angle, and energy-angle     2125 1451  220
distributions, as well as all residual and discrete + continuum   2125 1451  221
photon production cross sections for channels other than capture  2125 1451  222
(MT102) and reactions to discrete levels (MT51,etc.).             2125 1451  223
All data are generated with TALYS.                                2125 1451  224
                                                                  2125 1451  225
- MT5      : (n,anything) yields and energy-angle distributions   2125 1451  226
                                                                  2125 1451  227
MT5 contains, in this order,                                      2125 1451  228
For neutrons up to alpha particles and photons:                   2125 1451  229
- the production yields per particle for the whole energy range   2125 1451  230
- the secondary energy-angle distributions per particles which are2125 1451  231
  not represented by explicit MT numbers. On a secondary energy   2125 1451  232
  grid the relative emission spectra are given together with the  2125 1451  233
  parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular              2125 1451  234
  distributions. Inelastic scattering cross sections for discrete 2125 1451  235
  states have been broadened and added to the continuum spectra.  2125 1451  236
For each residual product:                                        2125 1451  237
- the production yields for the whole energy range.               2125 1451  238
- the recoil                                                      2125 1451  239
These distributions can be multiplied with MF3/MT5 to get         2125 1451  240
the production cross sections and (double-)differential cross     2125 1451  241
sections.                                                         2125 1451  242
                                                                  2125 1451  243
- MT16     : (n,2n) energy-angle distr. and photon production     2125 1451  244
                                                                  2125 1451  245
First, for each type of outgoing particle, the (trivial) integer  2125 1451  246
particle yields are given. Next, on a sufficiently dense incident 2125 1451  247
energy grid the secondary energy-angle distributions are          2125 1451  248
specified by means of the relative emission spectra and the       2125 1451  249
parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. 2125 1451  250
Next, the photon yield is tabulated as a function of incident     2125 1451  251
energy. For each incident energy, the photon production is given  2125 1451  252
for all discrete gamma lines present in the final nucleus. A      2125 1451  253
continuum photon distribution is added to this. We assume         2125 1451  254
isotropy for all produced gamma rays.                             2125 1451  255
                                                                  2125 1451  256
For the following MT-numbers, the same procedure as for MT16 is   2125 1451  257
followed:                                                         2125 1451  258
                                                                  2125 1451  259
- MT17 : (n,3n) energy-angle distr. and photon production         2125 1451  260
- MT22 : (n,na) energy-angle distr. and photon production         2125 1451  261
- MT28 : (n,np) energy-angle distr. and photon production         2125 1451  262
- MT91 : (n,n') continuum energy-angle distr. and phot. prod.     2125 1451  263
- MT649: (n,p) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     2125 1451  264
- MT699: (n,d) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     2125 1451  265
- MT749: (n,t) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     2125 1451  266
- MT809: (n,h) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     2125 1451  267
- MT849: (n,a) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     2125 1451  268
                                                                  2125 1451  269
##### MF8: RADIOACTIVE DECAY DATA                                 2125 1451  270
                                                                  2125 1451  271
For reactions to isomers, MF8 designates where the information    2125 1451  272
for isomeric versus ground state production, or residual          2125 1451  273
production can be found, i.e. for each MT number it points to     2125 1451  274
either MF6, MF9 or MF10.                                          2125 1451  275
                                                                  2125 1451  276
##### MF9: MULTIPLICITIES FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES  2125 1451  277
                                                                  2125 1451  278
MF9 is used for isomer production by non-threshold reactions.     2125 1451  279
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    2125 1451  280
as isomer.                                                        2125 1451  281
                                                                  2125 1451  282
##### MF10: CROSS SECTIONS FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES 2125 1451  283
                                                                  2125 1451  284
MF10 is used for isomer production by threshold reactions.        2125 1451  285
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    2125 1451  286
as isomer.                                                        2125 1451  287
                                                                  2125 1451  288
##### MF12: PHOTON PRODUCTION YIELD DATA                          2125 1451  289
                                                                  2125 1451  290
MF12 is used for the photon production for two types of reactions:2125 1451  291
- Reactions to discrete levels (MT51, etc.) For this transition   2125 1451  292
  probabilities are used (LO=2)                                   2125 1451  293
- Photons from neutron capture (MT102). Here multiplicities are   2125 1451  294
  given                                                           2125 1451  295
                                                                  2125 1451  296
##### MF14: PHOTON ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                          2125 1451  297
                                                                  2125 1451  298
All photon production is considered as isotropic                  2125 1451  299
                                                                  2125 1451  300
##### MF15: PHOTON ENERGY SPECTRA                                 2125 1451  301
                                                                  2125 1451  302
For capture (MT102), the photon energy spectrum is given.         2125 1451  303
                                                                  2125 1451  304
##### MF32: COVARIANCES OF RESONANCE PARAMETERS                   2125 1451  305
                                                                  2125 1451  306
In MF32, we store the covariances of resonance parameters,        2125 1451  307
and more details are given above in this description. In most     2125 1451  308
versions of TENDL, this information is now stored in MF33.        2125 1451  309
                                                                  2125 1451  310
##### MF33: COVARIANCES OF NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS                 2125 1451  311
                                                                  2125 1451  312
In MF33, we store the covariances of most, but not all, reaction  2125 1451  313
channels that are given in MF3. All covariances are generated     2125 1451  314
with the TASMAN code [kon19], which generates TALYS runs using    2125 1451  315
a Monte Carlo parameter method.                                   2125 1451  316
For each MT-number, the information consists of:                  2125 1451  317
1. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Ea (variances)                2125 1451  318
2. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Eb (correlations for the      2125 1451  319
   same reaction channel between different energies)              2125 1451  320
3. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Ea (correlations between      2125 1451  321
   different reaction channels for the same energy)               2125 1451  322
4. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Eb (correlations between      2125 1451  323
   different reaction channels for different energies)            2125 1451  324
Classes 1 and 2 are covered by NI-type subsubsections with        2125 1451  325
flag LB=5, followed by a LB=8 section which contains              2125 1451  326
the cross section variances multiplied by 1.e-3. Next, classes 3  2125 1451  327
and 4 are covered by flag LB=6 to account for the different       2125 1451  328
energy grids that two correlating MT-sections may have. Since     2125 1451  329
the total correlation matrix is fully symmetric, we only need to  2125 1451  330
include the correlation elements between different MT-numbers     2125 1451  331
once, and we do that in the subsection with the lowest of the     2125 1451  332
two MT-numbers. We include covariance information for all the     2125 1451  333
total cross sections, the lumped partial cross sections and the   2125 1451  334
individual inelastic cross sections per level (MT51,...). We do   2125 1451  335
not include covariances for MT600 and higher MT-numbers. For the  2125 1451  336
most important channels, we include cross-channel correlations.   2125 1451  337
                                                                  2125 1451  338
##### MF34: COVARIANCES OF ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                  2125 1451  339
                                                                  2125 1451  340
In MF34, we store the covariances of the elastic scattering       2125 1451  341
angular distributions that are given in MF4/MT2. All covariances  2125 1451  342
are generated with the TASMAN code [kon19], which generates       2125 1451  343
TALYS runs using a Monte Carlo parameter method. The tables are   2125 1451  344
restricted to MT2 and contain covariances for the first 6         2125 1451  345
Legendre coefficients. Both intra- and inter-correlations of the  2125 1451  346
various Legendre coefficients are given. As in MF33, the LB5      2125 1451  347
representation is used.                                           2125 1451  348
                                                                  2125 1451  349
##### MF40: COVARIANCES OF ISOMER PRODUCTION                      2125 1451  350
                                                                  2125 1451  351
For covariances of ground state and isomeric cross sections, the  2125 1451  352
same procedures as for MF33 are used.                             2125 1451  353
                                                                  2125 1451  354
